author: jsonline
title: State salutes
text:
Andy Barnhardt, Living Word Lutheran: The Timberwolves had a banner day Friday at Lake Country Lutheran, where they won the Midwest Classic title. Barnhardt, a senior who took third last year, set the pace, winning the 5,000-meter race in 16 minutes, 45.03 seconds.
GIRLS CROSS COUNTRY Zoe Goodmanson, Pewaukee: The freshman won for the fifth time in seven starts this season Thursday to lead the team to the Woodland Conference title. Goodmanson completed the 5,000-meter course at Pewaukee in 19:01.72, which was more than 20 seconds better than the second-place finisher.
FOOTBALL Matt Winters, Homestead: The Highlanders needed to beat two of the top teams in the North Shore Conference in the final two weeks to win a share of their 15th straight conference title. With Winters leading the way, they did just that. The senior running back had 146 yards and a touchdown in 29 carries in a 35-0 victory over Cedarburg on Friday. In Week 8, he totaled 165 yards and three touchdowns in 20 carries in a 35-13 victory over Whitefish Bay, which was previously undefeated in the league.
GIRLS GOLF Ashley Kulka, Beaver Dam: The senior scorched the course at University Ridge in Madison, shooting a 1-under-par 71 in the final round to make up a three-stroke deficit and win the Division 1 state title. Her final score of 2-over 146 was three strokes better than the runner-up.
BOYS SOCCER Jonathan Soto, Milwaukee Bradley Tech/Carmen: The Trojans won the outright City Conference championship Thursday with a 2-1 victory over second-place Reagan. Soto accounted for both goals, assisting on the first and scoring the game-winner at 85 minutes 20 seconds.
GIRLS SWIMMING Katie Hayes, Brown Deer/University School: The freshman won three events at the Watertown Invite Oct. 10. She took the 200-yard individual medley in 2 minutes, 16.86 seconds and the 100 breaststroke in 1:09.82. She also anchored the team's 200 medley relay to victory in 2:00.70.
GIRLS TENNIS Emma Corwin, Brookfield East: Despite losing a good portion of their 2014 lineup to graduation, the Spartans earned a return trip to the state tournament by winning their sectional at Racine Case. Corwin was the No. 1 singles champion and won two matches at individual state last week before losing.
BOYS VOLLEYBALL Aaron Plaisted, Wauwatosa East: The Red Raiders' outside hitter had a team-high 12 kills as they handed Brookfield East its first Greater Metro loss, 25-21, 25-22, 25-23, Wednesday.
GIRLS VOLLEYBALL Lexie Uselding, West Bend East: The senior outside hitter had 24 kills and posted a .316 hitting percentage for the Suns on Tuesday when they handed Oconomowoc its first Wisconsin Little Ten loss, in a 26-24, 25-22, 19-25, 25-22 victory. Uselding also made 11 digs, four aces, three blocks and was one of the team's leaders in serve receive for the match.
